Narrative Log
Dev Log - 2026-05-02

Today was a boundary-setting day. Not in the abstract sense, but in the practical one: the beta handoff path got more explicit, the upload/export story got less brittle, and the Pi coding-agent integration was broken into contracts that can actually be built in sequence. The effect was less “new capability” and more “the system stopped relying on assumption density.”

The first thread was the public beta path. The auth handoff was hardened, the public export workflow was added, and the media upload URLs were corrected so the bundle no longer depends on loose path behavior. That kind of work is easy to underestimate because it does not look like a product feature. But it matters because it narrows the gap between what the release says and what the release can actually do. The updated beta authorization instructions and release docs push in the same direction: fewer surprises for testers, fewer hidden steps for operators, and less room for the bundle to drift away from reality.

The second thread was the Pi integration campaign. Rather than treating “integrate Pi as a coding agent” as one large, fuzzy platform effort, the work was decomposed into a real sequence: define the envelope, create the adapter, wire the orchestration routes, connect the queue, and ingest results back into the thread flow. That is the right shape for a distributed execution path. It makes the boundaries visible. It also makes failure easier to reason about, because each seam can be verified separately instead of hiding behind a single big integration claim.

What stood out most is that this was structural work, not celebratory work. The current-state doc was refreshed to keep the short-horizon release truth aligned, and that matters because Codexify’s beta posture still depends on live runtime proof, not just documentation or a packaged artifact. So the day’s real achievement was not “we shipped Pi” or “we launched public beta.” It was that the system became more truthful about what is ready, what is planned, and what still needs validation.

That leaves the next move pretty clear. The public beta path should be proved end to end on the live stack, and the Pi integration should move from task scaffolding into implementation in the exact order the contracts now describe. The day made the system more legible. The next step is making it operationally undeniable.


